<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-167-152 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 029 795</DOCID><JOURNAL>Proceedings of the IEEE  May 1991 v79 n5 p595(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Large bandgap electronic materials and components. (Scanning theIssue) (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Davis, Robert F.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The thermal, mechanical, chemical and electronic properties ofdiamond, silicon carbide and cubic boron nitride give thematerials potential for use in high-power, high-temperature,high-frequency and optical microelectronic devices resistant toradiation damage.andP;  Previous research has shown that the electricalconductivity in power field-effect-transistors fabricated in largebandgap materials can be improved, using such physical parametersas peak electric field strength at avalanche breakdown, by two orthree orders of magnitude relative to comparable silicon devices.andO;It has also been shown that a considerable improvement is possiblein the on-state resistance of the devices.andP;  Recent discoveries ofseveral low temperature/low pressure process routes for thedeposition of films and coatings of diamond have made it animportant research topic in recent years.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Research and DevelopmentHigh TechnologyPhysicsRadiationSemiconductorsNew TechniqueMaterials AnalysisElectronicsIntegrated Circuit Fabrication.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>